<exploration xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="PA-8a-2">
  <p>
    Let <m>f(x) = \sin(x)</m> and, as in previous work, let <m>T(x) = c_0 + c_1 x + c_2 x^2 + c_3x^3</m>.  Our goal is to find the values of <m>c_0, \ldots, c_3</m> that make the sine function and its derivative values agree with those of the cubic polynomial <m>T</m> at <m>a = 0</m> and to study the resulting degree <m>3</m> approximation of the sine function.
  </p>


  <p>
    <ol marker="a.">
      <li>
        <p>
          As in previous work, the derivatives of <m>T(x)</m> and their respective values at <m>a = 0</m> are those shown in the following table.  Compute the various derivatives of <m>f(x) = \sin(x)</m> and evaluate them at <m>a = 0</m> accordingly, recording your results in the left side of <xref ref="T-8a-2-PA">Table</xref>.

          <table xml:id="T-8a-2-PA">
            <title>Formulas and values for <m>f(x) = \sin(x)</m> and <m>T(x)</m>.</title>
              <tabular top="minor" bottom="minor">
                <row>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>f(x)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>\sin(x)</m></cell>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>T(x)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>c_0 + c_1 x + c_2 x^2 + c_3 x^3</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>f'(x)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><fillin></fillin></cell>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>T'(x)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>c_1 + 2 c_2 x + 3 c_3 x^2</m></cell>
                </row>                
                <row>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>f''(x)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><fillin></fillin></cell>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>T''(x)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>2 c_2 + 6 c_3 x</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>f''(x)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><fillin></fillin></cell>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>T''(x)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>6 c_3</m></cell>
                </row>

                <row>
                  <cell></cell>
                  <cell></cell>
                  <cell></cell>
                  <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>f(0)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><fillin></fillin></cell>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>T(0)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>c_0</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>f'(0)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><fillin></fillin></cell>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>T'(0)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>c_1</m></cell>
                </row>                
                <row>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>f''(0)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><fillin></fillin></cell>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>T''(0)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>2c_2</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>f''(0)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><fillin></fillin></cell>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>T''(0)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>6c_3</m></cell>
                </row>
              </tabular>
            </table>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Now, set <m>T(0) = f(0)</m>, <m>, T'(0) = f'(0)</m>, <m>T''(0) = f''(0)</m>, and <m>T'''(0) = f'''(0)</m>.  What are the resulting values of <m>c_0, \ldots, c_3</m>?  What is the resulting formula for <m>T(x)</m>?
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Recall that the tangent line approximation <m>L</m> to <m>f(x) = \sin(x)</m> at <m>a = 0</m> is <m>L(x) = x</m>, as plotted in <xref ref="F-8a-2-PA">Figure</xref>.  On the same axes, plot the cubic approximation <m>T(x)</m> you found in (b).  What do you observe about the approximation <m>T</m> generates compared to the approximation <m>L</m> generates?
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="F-8a-2-PA">
          <caption>The function <m>f(x)=\sin(x)</m> and its tangent line approximation  <m>L(x) = x</m> near the point <m>(0,f(0))</m>.</caption>
          <image width="50%" source="images/8a_2_PA_2" />
        </figure>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Compute and compare <m>f(1) - L(1)</m> and <m>f(1) - T(1)</m>.  For what values of <m>x</m> does it appear that <m>|f(x) - L(x)| \le 0.1</m>? For what values of <m>x</m> does it appear that <m>|f(x) - L(x)| \le 0.1</m>?  How much better is the cubic approximation than the linear approximation?
        </p>
      </li>
      
    </ol>
  </p>
</exploration>

